<Author>Megabucks
<Content>Carolus a pleasant stay In late September 2005, we spent four nights at the Carolus Hotel in Florence. Overall, the experience was really just okay and I don't believe we would stay here the next time we visit Florence. We had just spent time in Rome and had terrific accomodations there, so the Carolus had a lot to live up to. Unfortunately, they disappointed a bit. The room was large and furnished with a queen sized bed, a long couch, desk and a few chairs. There was a nice view from our window facing the Duomo and the back of people's houses. One inconvenience about the room was the location of the electical switches behind the bathroom door, which opened OUT into the room. The wardrobe doors opened into the same space and well, let's just say there was a lot of door banging going on. The bathroom was a riot! At first, it was aggravating but eventually, we just prepared for an experience with every use. First of all, the lighting seemed left over from the 1950's. Fluorescent bulbs created a dim view. There was limited space to plop down one's bathroom essentials and at one point, it got so frustrating with things falling off the sink, that I just put the stuff on the floor to save it a trip! The most hysterical part was the shower. The hotel used some antiquated folding (!) shower door which was useless. Every towel in the room was used to sop up the wet after every shower. Even with the hand held shower, the floor was soaked afterward. When you're still a little jet-lagged and exhausted from walking tours, the last thing you want to do is have a fist-fight with a shower door at 7 a.m.! A shower rod and curtain would have been a better alternative. The front desk staff spoke English but were not especially warm or friendly. The morning waitstaff, serving coffee at the breakfast buffet, were welcoming and efficient. The hotel's location was probably the best thing about it. We were within walking distance of several good restaurants, a laundry/dry-cleaners, shopping, the Accademia and the Duomo. The Carolus was quiet with limited street traffic. Overall, it was really just a clean place to sleep at night with no extraordinary services. 
